Did it do you good?

270
00:46:21,527 --> 00:46:22,186
It wasn't good?

271
00:46:24,429 --> 00:46:26,829
You should've waited a week.

272
00:46:28,233 --> 00:46:29,825
I was hoping it would have...

273
00:46:29,868 --> 00:46:32,598
a homeopathic effect on your mood.

274
00:46:34,907 --> 00:46:36,033
Two octopus.

275
00:46:36,742 --> 00:46:38,903
- Like usual.
- Like usual.

276
00:46:44,349 --> 00:46:46,146
The octopus is tough.

277
00:46:50,389 --> 00:46:51,253
Is everything OK?

278
00:46:51,423 --> 00:46:53,550
The octopus is tough.

279
00:46:53,792 --> 00:46:54,952
Pardon me?

280
00:46:55,227 --> 00:46:57,957
Taste it. It won't stay the course.

281
00:46:58,130 --> 00:46:59,927
I'll change it right away.

282
00:47:27,125 --> 00:47:29,116
Belinda, come here.

283
00:47:31,663 --> 00:47:34,097
I don't understand.
What's he saying?

284
00:47:36,802 --> 00:47:38,531
He's very mad.

285
00:47:39,538 --> 00:47:44,532
He says, "What's wrong with
the octopus? It's like cement!"

286
00:47:45,911 --> 00:47:48,436
I have the best quality octopus!

287
00:47:48,580 --> 00:47:51,481
If you're not happy,
go fish them yourself!

288
00:47:59,157 --> 00:48:04,185
Can someone here tell me what's
going on with the damn octopus?

289
00:48:04,630 --> 00:48:06,928
Who went to get them this morning?

290
00:48:08,100 --> 00:48:10,091
I went to get them.

291
00:48:10,369 --> 00:48:12,360
Head usually gets them,

292
00:48:13,171 --> 00:48:14,968
he always chooses them.

293
00:48:15,107 --> 00:48:17,200
- I know.
- He hasn't been in.

294
00:48:17,442 --> 00:48:21,435
I tried calling him a few times.
Nobody answers.

295
00:48:21,780 --> 00:48:22,644
He might be sick.

296
00:48:24,182 --> 00:48:25,706
I'll go and get him.

297
00:48:27,452 --> 00:48:31,354
I don't know, Miguel came
3 or 4 times already...

298
00:48:31,690 --> 00:48:34,022
We're afraid something happened.

299
00:50:02,981 --> 00:50:04,141
Be careful.

300
00:50:05,217 --> 00:50:06,946
Pull on the collar.

301
00:50:07,152 --> 00:50:09,143
OK, we can take the mask off.

302
00:50:11,890 --> 00:50:13,118
Are you OK?

303
00:50:21,033 --> 00:50:23,695
- Is it untied?
- Yes, you can go.

304
00:50:27,172 --> 00:50:28,662
Feels good to get out.

305
00:50:28,907 --> 00:50:30,898
- Everything fine?
- Looks like it.

306
00:51:55,760 --> 00:51:56,920
It's him.

307
00:51:57,529 --> 00:51:59,997
Who decided to cremate him?

308
00:52:00,132 --> 00:52:01,565
Good question.

309
00:52:01,933 --> 00:52:04,026
He wasn't supposed to be cremated.

310
00:52:04,870 --> 00:52:06,394
Oh no?

311
00:52:07,038 --> 00:52:07,868
Oops!

312
00:52:08,406 --> 00:52:12,604
Our condolences.
Do you need a bag?

313
00:52:23,488 --> 00:52:27,015
You sure you don't want me
to improvise a little ceremony?

314
00:52:28,193 --> 00:52:30,093
I'm sure he'd like it.

315
00:52:31,163 --> 00:52:32,460
No, thank you.

316
00:52:33,532 --> 00:52:35,159
That's very kind of you.

317
00:52:35,300 --> 00:52:37,825
My father only believed
in what he saw.

318
00:52:38,136 --> 00:52:39,797
Well, now he sees God.

319
00:52:42,541 --> 00:52:43,974
Einstein Karsan.

320
00:52:44,242 --> 00:52:47,234
- Could you please speak up?
- Einstein Karsen.

321
00:52:47,846 --> 00:52:49,108
Could you spell it?

322
00:52:49,247 --> 00:52:51,772
A-n-n-s-t-e-i-n, Carson with a C...

323
00:52:51,917 --> 00:52:55,284
Excuse me, it's Annstein Karson.
It's with a K.

324
00:55:47,692 --> 00:55:49,455
FUTURE

325
00:55:50,528 --> 00:55:52,928
Bibiane, Flo Fabert's daughter.

326
00:56:37,575 --> 00:56:41,033
Obituaries, prayers, thank yous.

327
00:56:55,193 --> 00:56:56,717
No, thank you.

328
00:56:58,296 --> 00:57:00,457
That's nice, thank you. But...

329
00:57:01,866 --> 00:57:03,356
my father believed only...

330
00:57:03,501 --> 00:57:06,299
Excuse me, I'd like to see
Annstein Carson, please.

331
00:57:06,638 --> 00:57:09,198
- Who?
- Annstein Carson.

332
00:57:09,841 --> 00:57:11,433
Could you spell that?

333
00:57:11,643 --> 00:57:14,874
A-n-n-s-t-e-i-n,

334
00:57:15,914 --> 00:57:18,439
C-a-r-s-o-n.

335
00:57:19,484 --> 00:57:21,884
It's Annstein Karson with a K.

336
00:57:22,554 --> 00:57:26,820
I'm his neighbour, we'd say hi,
when we'd cross on the street.

337
00:57:27,125 --> 00:57:29,320
I thought he was all alone so...

338
00:57:30,161 --> 00:57:31,560
I came over here...

339
00:57:31,596 --> 00:57:33,564
to say hi one last time.

340
00:57:34,165 --> 00:57:36,725
I didn't know he had a son.
Had I known...

341
00:57:37,135 --> 00:57:38,500
I shouldn't be here.

342
00:57:38,636 --> 00:57:40,661
I didn't know he had a neighbour.

343
00:57:41,439 --> 00:57:44,499
He lived inside his head,
neighbours're rare there.

344
00:57:45,944 --> 00:57:46,933
Know him long?

345
00:57:47,846 --> 00:57:48,835
No.

346
00:57:49,614 --> 00:57:50,410
Not really.

347
00:57:54,018 --> 00:57:56,009
Where can I get a tooth brush?

348
00:57:58,256 --> 00:57:59,883
A tooth brush?

349
00:58:00,592 --> 00:58:02,560
There's a drugstore over there.

350
00:58:02,760 --> 00:58:05,354
Do you know where I can get a coffee?

351
00:58:06,464 --> 00:58:09,729
Right next to the drugstore.

352
00:58:10,602 --> 00:58:13,002
- Do you want to have a coffee with me?
- No...

353
00:58:14,706 --> 00:58:16,037
I can't, I'm sorry.

354
00:58:16,207 --> 00:58:17,299
I understand.

355
00:58:17,642 --> 00:58:20,236
A coffee by yourself is quite boring.

356
00:58:20,445 --> 00:58:23,437
In fact, it's really... very boring.

357
00:58:26,184 --> 00:58:27,310
For my father?

358
00:58:30,855 --> 00:58:31,981
How can I say no?

359
00:58:32,524 --> 00:58:34,151
I don't know anyone here.

360
00:58:39,063 --> 00:58:40,553
How did he die?

361
00:58:40,899 --> 00:58:41,695
You don't know?

362
00:58:42,200 --> 00:58:43,292
He was poisoned.

363
00:58:43,568 --> 00:58:47,299
My father remarried
a somewhat jealous, Haitian lady.

364
00:58:47,739 --> 00:58:50,367
When he left, she put a curse on him.

365
00:58:50,508 --> 00:58:52,271
She was in a voodoo gang.

366
00:58:52,410 --> 00:58:54,970
I could've dug him up,
and he'd be a zombie.

367
00:58:55,313 --> 00:58:57,873
But the idiots cremated him.

368
00:59:01,286 --> 00:59:02,275
Thanks.

369
00:59:05,823 --> 00:59:06,812
Thank you.

370
00:59:09,727 --> 00:59:11,786
No, he got hit by a car.

371
00:59:13,164 --> 00:59:14,358
I thought so.

372
00:59:15,400 --> 00:59:16,867
What do you do?

373
00:59:18,036 --> 00:59:20,231
- I'm a flight attendant.
- Really?

374
00:59:20,371 --> 00:59:21,497
What airline?

375
00:59:22,040 --> 00:59:24,133
It depends, it varies...

376
00:59:26,144 --> 00:59:27,168
Staying long?

377
00:59:27,445 --> 00:59:32,041
No, I'm leaving tomorrow morning.

378
00:59:32,216 --> 00:59:35,447
I've a favour to ask.
It's my father's things...

379
00:59:37,488 --> 00:59:40,184
I'm... I'm already late,
I'm sorry.

380
00:59:49,534 --> 00:59:51,126
Thanks for the coffee.

381
00:59:55,406 --> 00:59:56,395
You're tough.

382
01:00:30,708 --> 01:00:34,007
I have to see my father's co-workers.
It won't take long.

383
01:01:33,271 --> 01:01:36,399
I wish that your father's killer...

384
01:01:36,908 --> 01:01:40,571
dies of a slow and atrocious death.

385
01:01:43,781 --> 01:01:47,740
I wish that the killer dies
in the most cruel solitude.

386
01:01:52,523 --> 01:01:55,458
I wish that he dies disembowelled,

387
01:01:55,693 --> 01:01:56,921
devoured by dogs.

388
01:02:03,534 --> 01:02:05,593
If I catch him, I kill him.

389
01:02:36,968 --> 01:02:38,128
He'll die,

390
01:02:38,703 --> 01:02:41,035
that's all that's written.

391
01:02:50,348 --> 01:02:52,111
That was a stiff drink.

392
01:02:53,384 --> 01:02:54,783
Yeah, quite.

393
01:03:17,074 --> 01:03:20,566
Well that's it.
That represents a whole life.

394
01:03:23,080 --> 01:03:24,411
Now I have to...

395
01:03:24,749 --> 01:03:27,081
sort it all out before the morning.

396
01:03:27,518 --> 01:03:29,543
I can't open them alone.

397
01:03:34,392 --> 01:03:35,620
Don't worry.

398
01:04:27,612 --> 01:04:29,102
It still works.

399
01:04:31,349 --> 01:04:32,543
Garbage.

400
01:04:52,770 --> 01:04:54,328
I'll keep that.

401
01:04:58,743 --> 01:05:00,176
The ring.

402
01:05:02,113 --> 01:05:03,375
That.

403
01:05:04,048 --> 01:05:05,106
This.

404
01:05:10,021 --> 01:05:11,420
Here.

405
01:05:12,490 --> 01:05:14,651
For you, to protect you from the cold...

406
01:05:14,892 --> 01:05:16,883
and other stuff like voodoo.

407
01:05:20,164 --> 01:05:21,426
Thank you.

408
01:05:24,669 --> 01:05:26,193
What time's your flight?

409
01:05:26,337 --> 01:05:29,670
I don't know what to do
about my father.

410
01:05:30,808 --> 01:05:31,968
And your mother?

411
01:05:32,109 --> 01:05:33,508
She died when I was 3.

412
01:05:33,911 --> 01:05:35,310
She drowned.

413
01:05:36,447 --> 01:05:39,109
My father never set foot
on a boat again.

414
01:05:39,483 --> 01:05:42,850
He wanted to be buried at sea,
with my mother, but now...

415
01:05:43,254 --> 01:05:44,721
he's only powder, so...

416
01:05:44,989 --> 01:05:47,423
You can still do it.

417
01:05:48,326 --> 01:05:52,626
It's just that...
a sailor is... it's whole.

418
01:05:52,863 --> 01:05:56,629
I can't dust the waves,
it's not like him either.

419
01:05:56,934 --> 01:06:00,335
I'm afraid...
it'll look a little stupid.

420
01:06:00,738 --> 01:06:02,035
No.

421
01:06:05,576 --> 01:06:07,635
You speak Norwegian?

422
01:06:07,878 --> 01:06:09,368
It's been a while.

423
01:06:09,513 --> 01:06:10,673
Listen.

424
01:06:18,356 --> 01:06:19,823
Yes... it goes...

425
01:06:22,426 --> 01:06:23,893
And then it's...

426
01:06:25,129 --> 01:06:26,756
What does it mean?

427
01:06:26,931 --> 01:06:32,927
Rip their heads off, empty their skulls,
drink from the skulls of our enemies.

428
01:06:33,471 --> 01:06:35,268
Then it talks about
opening up the belly,

429
01:06:35,406 --> 01:06:38,068
eating the liver alive. It's folklore.

430
01:07:01,565 --> 01:07:03,556
- We didn't get much sleep.
- No.

431
01:07:04,335 --> 01:07:06,599
You'll sleep on the plane.

432
01:07:06,637 --> 01:07:09,003
Thank you very much.

433
01:07:10,174 --> 01:07:11,539
You're nice.

434
01:07:17,214 --> 01:07:19,045
I'll think about you a lot.

435
01:07:22,386 --> 01:07:23,580
I know.

436
01:07:59,056 --> 01:08:00,045
I forgot to say...

437
01:08:05,196 --> 01:08:07,130
I wanted to make love with you.

438
01:08:15,005 --> 01:08:16,563
That's my table, my chairs.

439
01:08:16,707 --> 01:08:18,937
That's a picture of my best friend.

440
01:08:20,010 --> 01:08:22,240
That's my fridge, my stove,

441
01:08:22,513 --> 01:08:24,504
my plates, my glasses,

442
01:08:26,550 --> 01:08:28,017
my carpet.

443
01:08:28,719 --> 01:08:31,119
That's my bed, my sheets...

444
01:08:31,856 --> 01:08:33,346
my clothes...

445
01:08:35,960 --> 01:08:39,487
that's a couch, windows...
that's my home.

446
01:09:10,794 --> 01:09:12,352
You're a frogman.

447
01:09:12,963 --> 01:09:14,931
And you're not a flight attendant.

448
01:09:16,367 --> 01:09:18,733
You're not my father's neighbour, either.

